        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(client): write client config atomically to prevent corruption on interrupted save",
        "body": "## Problem\n\n`saveClientConfig` rewrote `~/.config/clickclack/config.json` with `os.WriteFile`. A process interruption or failed write could truncate the live config and leave later CLI commands unable to parse it.\n\n## Fix\n\nStage the complete config in a sibling temporary file, apply the intended mode, sync and close it, then atomically rename it over the destination.\n\nMaintainer hardening preserves the existing credential-file contract:\n\n- New configs remain private (`0600`).\n- Existing writable modes are preserved.\n- Existing read-only configs still reject writes instead of becoming replaceable through parent-directory permissions.\n- Valid symlinks remain symlinks; dangling symlinks fail safely and remain intact.\n- Non-regular targets are rejected.\n- Failed staging or rename paths remove their temporary files.\n\n## Verification\n\nExact head: `3c71b50dd95a5beb45ee7e8333f83c96c30604a8`\n\n- `pnpm check`\n- `go test ./...`\n- `go test -v ./apps/api/cmd/clickclack/ -run 'TestWriteClientConfigFile'` — 6/6 passed: private creation, writable-mode preservation, read-only refusal, valid symlink preservation, dangling symlink safety, and rename-failure cleanup.\n- Autoreview: clean, no accepted/actionable findings; patch correct at 0.82 confidence.\n\nThis keeps the contributor's atomic-write direction while adding the missing regression coverage and repairing the permission and symlink edge cases found during maintainer review.\n",
        "branch": "fix/atomic-client-config-write",
